    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Another way of fixing this would be to let peers be added to `PeerPool` without the DAO fork check, and then perform the check in `ChainSyncer` by keeping a list of peers for which the check is pending and having its `_handle_msg_loop()` do the following for every msg read from the queue:\r\n   1. If peer has passed DAO fork check, process msg normally  \r\n   2. Else if cmd is not BlockHeaders, add it to the list of msgs received by that peer and return\r\n   3. Else if cmd is BlockHeaders\r\n    3.1 If DAO fork check is successful, handle all previously received messages from the peer\r\n    3.2 Else disconnect from peer and discard all previous messages\r\n\r\nEDIT: Some issues with this approach are:\r\n1. The `PeerPool` does not guarantee that peers are on the same side of the fork as us, so we might end up having to duplicate the check in other `PeerPoolSubscriber`s\r\n2. The msgs from peers pending the DAO check will be added to the `ChainSyncer` queue, and there may be a big backlog of msgs from other peers, which makes it hard for us to decide when to timeout and give up on a peer that is pending the DAO check\r\n",
